column9: One Again: Sexual Violence Services Program
column10: 'One Again' is NYAWC's sexual violence support program. We offer advocacy, confidential counseling, and integrated holistic wellness services, free of cost, to any survivor of sexual violence at any point in their lifespan. We serve any survivor, irrespective of age, ethnicity, gender identification, and sexual orientation. We also have legal staff that work with survivors on immigration relief. Our staff speak 18+ Asian languages and our confidential helpline runs 24/7 to provide crisis support: 1-888-888-7702.

We have a structured program where each student is to attend tutoring for 1 hour Monday through Thursday. In the hour of tutoring, our college advisor helps students with their college applications as well as SAT prep. On Mondays and Wednesdays, each student has access to 1 hour of recreation. On Tuesdays and Thursdays, we have workshops and presentations from different organizations on different topics (i.e. Fire safety, CPR, the fundamentals of savings, etc.). On Fridays we take the students out on trips.

Grace Outreach (GO) operates out of an easily-accessible location in the middle of the Mott Haven section of the South Bronx, has healthy finances, and enjoys active, engaged Board leadership and stewardship.  Our students are primarily low-income women of color living in the Bronx. They first join us to acquire their high school equivalency diploma. In 2014-15 the organization served over 375 women across 3 inter-related programs, TASC/HSE (High School Equivalency) Prep, Career Prep, and College Prep. Since its inception, GO has enabled over 1,100 women to earn their High School Equivalency diploma, 100+ have enrolled in career and technical training programs,  and over 200 women have finished GO's College Prep course and matriculated at CUNY. Putting students on track to enroll in college has been a major focus of GO for 8 years.

column10: The Bronx GEAR UP Network serves 2,322 students in 8 Bronx public schools: MS 45, PS 194, IS 254, MS 280, MS/HS 242, MS/HS 368, MS 390, and MS/HS 505. The large majority of students in these schools come from low-income households, with rates of eligibility for free and reduced lunch ranging from 80%-95%. Four project objectives are (1) to increase middle school students' academic performance and preparation for a successful high school experience; (2) to increase high school students' academic performance and preparation for postsecondary enrollment and persistence; (3) to support GEAR UP students' persistence in postsecondary education programs; and (4) to increase student and family engagement in activities designed to promote awareness of and access to postsecondary education options.

Scholars from every grade participate in Career Readiness workshops that develop problem-solving, research, analysis, leadership, presentation and critical thinking skills. Finally, students participate in social enrichment activities of their choice such as basketball, yoga, dance or volleyball.

column10: The KHCC Teen Center serves youth ages 11 to 21 years in grades 6-12, and often into young adulthood and college. During the previous program year, the Teen Center enrolled 257 youth, 49% female and 51% male. There were 54 middle school students (21%) ranging in age from 11-14, 191 high school students (74%) ranging in age from 14-21, and 12 youth participants who were 19-21 years old (5%), and either out of school, recently graduated, or attending college. Eighty-three percent of our active youth (213 participants) reported as eligible for free or reduced price lunch at school. The vast majority of program participants are living below 125% of the poverty level where low-wage jobs support the household. A significant proportion of our participants grow up in Bronx homes with multiple families living together in compromised housing situations. School failure, violence, substance abuse, gang involvement, and self-destructive behaviors are common experiences among neighborhood youth. Some participants are special needs youth who exhibit behavioral disorders and learning disabilities. Many youth are linked to neglectful family environments and interact with the justice and/or social service systems.

column9: Edgies Clubhouse of the Educational Alliance's Boys & Girls Club of America
column10: The Edgies Clubhouse of the Educational Alliance is a community-based non-for profit organization that caters specifically to culturally and socio-economically diverse high school students from partnering schools in the Lower East Side region of NYC. Among the plethora of services we offer, participating students receive social/emotional learning, extracurricular activities (i.e. cooking, dancing, basketball, fitness & conditioning, etc.), and College/SAT Prep for high school Juniors and Seniors.

A Better Chance is the oldest and only national organization of its kind changing the life trajectory for academically talented youth of color via access to rigorous and prestigious educational opportunities for students in grades 6-12.  Our mission is to increase substantially the number of well-educated young people of color who are capable of assuming positions of responsibility and leadership in American society.  We carry out our mission through our signature College Preparatory Schools Program, which annually recruits, refers and supports about 500 Scholars at more than 300 Member Schools in 27 states.

Founded in 1999, Breakthrough New York is a college access and success program whose mission is to help highly motivated, low income students earn admission to and successfully graduate from selective high schools and colleges. BTNY currently serves over 360 students through rigorous academic and career readiness programming and academic placement support.

REACH Prep helps motivated and talented Black and Latino students from underserved communities in Fairfield and Westchester Counties and the Bronx gain admission to and thrive in rigorous independent schools. Upon placement, students benefit from a twelve-year educational continuum, including comprehensive academic enrichment, leadership training and supplementary individual and family guidance, which prepares them to succeed at competitive colleges.

Summer on the Hill (SOH) is a year-round, supplemental enrichment program for promising, low-income public school students from the Bronx, Washington Heights, and Harlem. 

Founded in 1994, SOH has now served 1,300 NYC students with accelerated academic classes, instruction in the arts and sports, test prep classes, and college trips, and has offered students and parents guidance on school and college choices.

The primary entrance point for SOH is the end of second grade. Students must be nominated by their public schools and meet SOH academic and financial criteria for admission. SOH is held in two components:

— The six-year Grade 3-8 program includes a yearly six-week summer session bridged by a mandatory 18-session Saturday school year program. Both summer and school-year sessions are intensely academic, with accelerated classes in language arts, math, and science.

— The High School Program continues the SOH community for Grade 3-8 Program alumni. HS students may participate in SOH's PSAT/SAT prep classes, college counseling, college visits, workshops for students and parents, and additional college-readiness activities.

column8: Barnard College Academic Success and Enrichment Programs

The student body is currently comprised of approximately 1300 academically gifted and ambitious individuals who are dedicated to life-long learning and achievement. Students are offered AP courses in English, Literature, Physics, Calculus AB & BC, Art History to name a few.

Cornelia Connelly Center (CCC) champions girls at risk, empowering them to realize their full potential from middle school through college and beyond.



We embrace each child entering our program, walking with her on a decades-long journey of growth in mind, heart and spirit. Our challenging, joyful middle school, Connelly Middle School of the Holy Child, fosters skills, resilience and compassion, while our innovative, holistic Graduate Support Program supports college aspirations and completion.

OneGoal teachers work with cohorts of students for 3 years, from junior year of high school through the first day of sophomore year of college.

CUNY Start provides intensive preparation in academic reading/writing, pre-college math, and “college success” advisement for students entering CUNY with significant remedial needs based on the results of their CUNY Assessment Tests. The goal of the program is to help students prepare for college-level coursework and reduce or eliminate any remedial needs prior to starting credit-bearing courses.

If you are planning to attend a CUNY community college as a first-time college student, we invite you to apply to College Discovery (CD)! This unique program provides eligible students with financial, academic, and counseling resources designed to help you earn your 2-year associate degree and then transfer to a 4-year bachelor's degree program upon graduation.

The BEOC Pre-Freshman Academy/College Preparation Program is designed to help individuals make the transition into college and acquire skills and knowledge necessary to successfully navigate college environment and complete college courses. This program is designed for students in need of skills development in English (reading & writing) and Math (pre-algebra & algebra) over 2 terms/15 weeks. Individuals who need intervention in one subject only (English or Math) may register for 1 term/7.5 weeks. Students are expected to have applied to college before enrolling at BEOC or while enrolled in the program.

CUNY Accelerated Study in Associate Programs (ASAP)
column10: Accelerated Study in Associate Programs (ASAP) provides financial, academic and personal supports to help students to stay on track and earn their degree as soon as possible. ASAP benefits include free unlimited MetroCards, textbook vouchers, tuition waivers (if applicable), personalized advisement, career development services, and academic support.

AF provides comprehensive college access and success services to 700 high school students and 150 college-going high school graduates. Achievement First schools provide all of our students with the academic and character skills they need to graduate from top colleges, to succeed in a competitive world and to serve as the next generation of leaders in our communities.

Although our program office is based in Manhattan, we provide service to clients (high school students, immigrant students, adult learners and disconnected youth) who reside in the NY or NJ. We offer workshops in public HS, with consideration of location and time, and collaborative schedules. Parent workshops are currently facilitated in Cantonese, Mandarin and English.

column8: The Boys' Club of New York
column10: BCNY provides college access and career training services to our members, the vast majority of whom are low income and Black or Latino. We also place boys in independent day and boarding schools.

CARA trains students who have completed one year of college to work with incoming students to support them through the obstacles to persistence through their first year of college. Trained college students provide one-on-one support, facilitate workshops, connect students to campus resources, and host events that help integrate students onto campus.
column11: College Access: Research & Action (CARA) - CUNY Graduate Center

column10: CBI places full-time college guidance experts in public schools to work one-on-one with every student as early as the sixth grade. We combine intimate knowledge of our students and trusted connections with a diverse network of colleges, enabling us to optimize college placement and maximize financial aid. Our comprehensive approach creates a culture of success in each of our partner high schools. And the results are clear — we have 14 consecutive years of demonstrated success in increasing the college enrollment and attainment rate for low-income students. For CBI students, the question is not “if” but “where” they will go to college.

column9: NYU Community College Transfer Opportunity Program (CCTOP)
column10: CCTOP is a scholarship and advisement program for students transferring to NYU from 14 partner community colleges.

Center for Achieving Future Education College Access Center provides one-to-one college access and success counseling and financial aid services to high school students, young adults, and adults. We service students in 9th grade through their first year of college through One-to-One College Advising.

Asistance with Applying for Financial Aid College Visits

SAT Prep registration Early College Awareness Programs

College Advising

column8: SCO Family of Services/Center for Family Life
column9: Center for Family Life at Sunset Park High School
column10: CFL's comprehensive partnership with Sunset Park High School ensures every student is known and supported and fosters a college-going culture. CFL social work and youth development staff collaborate with teachers in a school day advisory and internship program that engages all 1300+ SPHS students in intensive support for academic goal?setting, college preparation, and social and emotional learning. Afterschool programming at SPHS includes a diverse menu of academic and arts enrichment, sports and recreation, service learning and internships, college readiness and career exploration.

College Access Services: We provide 1:1 College Advising Services to high school students and young adults. In addition, we offer SAT Prep, college visits, and financial aid assistance. We also provide campus based college success advising to all of our students who matriculate to college.

Computer Resource Centers (CRCs) are located within Recreation Centers and provide free digital learning resources for center members of all ages and abilities. Starting with one public computer lab at Al Smith Recreation Center in 1997, there are now CRCs throughout the five boroughs. CRCs aim to increase community technology resources through providing internet access and technology education in New York City communities.

column8: CUNY College Opportunity to Prepare for Employment (COPE)
column9: CUNY College Opportunity to Prepare for Employment (COPE)
column10: COPE assists CUNY students who are receiving public assistance achieve academic excellence, graduate on time, and find employment. Program services include personal and academic advising, professional development workshops, career development and work study opportunities, and assistance in compliance with HRA policies.

CUNY Prep serves 16-18 year old students who have left high school and are pursuing their HSED and desire to continue to college.  We provide support in completing college applications, FAFSA, and CUNY entrance exam instruction.

East Harlem Tutorial Program (EHTP) gives kids the opportunities they would have if they were born 20 blocks south. And we've been doing it for more than 55 years. We teach reading, math and science, provide one-to-one tutoring, prepare kids for college, help them get accepted, and build the social skills they'll need to succeed.

For over 30 years, Legal Outreach has prepared urban youth from underserved communities in New York City to compete at high academic levels by using intensive legal and educational programs as tools for fostering vision, developing skills, enhancing confidence, and facilitating the pursuit of higher education. We use law to attract junior high school students to academic programs that inspire and motivate them to strive for academic success. From the 8th through 12th grades, students work after school, on weekends, and during summers to build the skills and confidence they need to achieve their goals. Once in college, students who wish to pursue law school are eligible to participate in our College to Law School Pipeline Diversity Program.

Guttman Community College (CUNY), located in midtown Manhattan, is an open admissions college. Applicants who have a high school diploma or GED are welcome to apply. First-year students are required to attend full-time.  Guttman offers students a supportive environment that connects classroom learning, career development and volunteer service opportunities.

Harlem RBI is a sports-based youth development program that provides team-based athletic activities, academic enrichment, social emotional learning, and college advising services for youth in East Harlem and the South Bronx. We offer programs for elementary, middle school, high school, and college-aged youth.

iMentor builds mentoring relationships that empower students from low-income communities to graduate high school, succeed in college, and achieve their ambitions. Students work with their mentors one-on-one, in-person, and online to develop strong personal relationships, nurture a college aspiration, navigate the college application process, and build critical skills that lead to college success.

In addition to its afterschool programs, PowerPlay NYC provides an intensive summer leadership academy for 50 high school girls in New York City. The majority of the girls are primarily low-income, first generation, college bound students that qualify for free and reduced lunch. We provide them with college and career readiness, planned parenthood instruction, and exposure to new sports. They are provided a two week mini-internship and then transition to a Youth Mentor Coach within our afterschool programs. They continue to be a part of our network, as we provide them with monthly college trips and other activities.

KIPP NYC College Prep has a team of dedicated college and career counselors to ensure that every student applies to college and has an understanding of the many career options available to them. We support juniors in SAT preparation, college exploration and applications for pre-college summer programming. We support seniors through the college application, financial aid, and selection process to ensure our students attend the best fit school with the highest graduation rate and best financial aid packaging possible.
Learning Communities are when two or more courses are linked together and curriculum is integrated.

Minds Matter is a 3-year intensive program that supports students' dreams of attending college. Students meet with instructors and are assigned mentors to navigate them through Writing and Critical Thinking and Math skills development, standardized test preparation, and application writing. 100% of Minds Matter students are accepted to 4-year colleges.

MLT College Prep seeks to prepare under-represented minority students with solid academic track records for success for fast-track entry-level jobs at top employers.

Pariticpating undergraduate juniors or seniors from 100+ colleges across the nation - Rising Leaders - are paired with a dedicated MLT Coach, who works with the Rising Leader to gain personal clarity around how his or her strengths and passions translate to career goals. Together, Rising Leaders and MLT coaches design personalized career roadmaps to ensure that each Rising Leader is prepared to meet or exceed projected goals by the end of the program. Rising Leaders attend in-person workshops hosted and facilitated by MLT's corporate partners, and receive insight and guidance from the MLT network of over 4,000 other Rising Leaders and many more volunteer executives.  

MLT College Prep has an internship and full-time placement rate of over 95% at top organizations across a variety of sectors.
Our Afterschool program serves middle school students grades 6-8. We offer App Development, Martial Arts, Basketball, Drama, Fashion and Film Production.

Our partnership schools target students who are over age and under credited.  We offer students the social, emotional and academic supports that they need to succesffuly complete high school and create a plan for their future.
Our program provides older immigrant youth with college and career counseling, tutoring, and support services.

PENCIL works at the intersection of school needs and business expertise to bring together the best ideas, talent, and resources across sectors to improve public student and school performance and enhance workforce pathways. PENCIL partners NYC businesses with a NYC public school to improve their capacity to help students reach their college and career goals. Business volunteers have valuable experience with what is required to succeed in college and careers; they have knowledge and skills that schools and students need. PENCIL works with business leaders to provide access to workplace experiences, college and career planning, and professional skills. PENCIL staff provides hands-on support to each school and business to create a college & career partnership that meets their needs, has clearly established goals and expectations, and has a positive impact on students and schools. PENCIL'S toolkit of codified resources and curricula can be adapted based on the expertise of volunteers.

column8: Single Stop at Queensborough Community College
column10: Queensborough Community College strives to assist students in achieving academic success. Students often face the challenge of having to choose between college or life demands. The Single Stop office is here to connect students with social services and resources to overcome these obstacles.

Saturday Program was founded by Cooper undergrads in 1968. Today it enrolls over 200 NYC public high school students in intensive, full day Saturday classes in: Graphics, Drawing, Painting, Sculpture, Architecture, Sound Composition & Portfolio Preparation. Classes run from October-April. Writing workshops are integrated within the visual curricula & college counseling and support are provided to all seniors & juniors, with 85-90% of students accepted to colleges. All instruction & materials are free.

Serve low-income, first generation middle and high school students from the Harlems, Bronx, Washington Heights and other parts of New York by providing a host of free educational services and guidance.

Since 1990, our one-of-a-kind program has helped low-income students across the country rise to their potential and become beacons of change in their communities, through a customized circle of support and weekly meetings with a professional mentor.

Single Stop is a non-profit organization that partners with, mostly, community based organizations throughout the five boroughs to help people access resources and benefits that will lead to self-sufficiency. At every Single Stop you will find a financial counselor, legal assistance, tax preparation and someone who will conduct a benefits screening and help you to access the benefits you're eligible for.

The Academic Support Program helps formerly incarcerated women achieve their college degrees. ASP provides academic counseling, financial development, wellness and resource referrals, scholarships, book assistance, transportation assistance and school supply assistance.

column8: Collegiate Science and Technology Entry Program
column9: Collegiate Science and Technology Entry Program
column10: The Biology Collegiate Science & Technology Entry Program (CSTEP) is funded by the New York State Education Department and is designed to: 1) increase historically underrepresented and economically disadvantaged student awareness of the biological sciences as career options, and 2) increase the numbers of these students who complete pre-professional or professional education programs of study that lead to licensure in CSTEP-targeted professions.

column9: The Carroll and Milton Petrie Student Emergency Fund
column10: The Carroll and Milton Petrie Student Emergency Fund provides quick response grants to matriculated students who are facing short-term financial emergencies. The Petrie Fund's emergency grants seek to help students with limited means to remain in school, rather than be forced to take a leave of absence or drop out of school.

The CDF-New York Beat the Odds® scholarship program provides social and academic college readiness programming to high school students that are working hard to overcome tremendous obstacles in their personal lives, who demonstrate academic achievement, and give back to their community.



Ten sophomores will be selected from the nomination pool, and will have the opportunity to apply for scholarships provided by the Children's Defense Fund-New York during their senior year.

The Center keenly focuses on meeting the needs of the surrounding community. The Center is a non-profit, multi-service organization focusing primarily on the needs of children and low-income families as well as out-of-school and out-of-work youth.

The Children's Aid Society (CAS) Adolescence Division College Success Program currently supports 75 high school graduates, most of whom entered college this fall 2015 in the NYC area. Students are supported academically, financially, and socio-emotionally through bi-weekly check-ins, one-on-one or in groups, by phone, email or in-person.
The College Prep program provides academic assistance in Reading, Writing and Math to prepare eligible students for the college entrance exam.

The CUNY Black Male Initiative is a University-wide student development initiative with more than 30 projects focused on increasing matriculation, retention and graduation rates of underrepresented students, particularly men of color. CUNY BMI is one expression of CUNY's commitment to access and diversity. CUNY BMI projects are open to all academically eligible students, faculty and staff, without regard for race, gender or national origin.

column8: Settlement Housing Fund, Inc./ DREAMS YouthBuild
column10: The DREAMS Youth Build & Young Adult Training Program is a Brooklyn based, comprehensive HSE and Construction training opportunity for youth age 17 1/2- 24 years old.

The Fiver Children's Foundation is a youth development organization that provides a commitment of 10 years to children from underserved communities in the New York area. Our organization aims to deconstruct some of the effects of poverty and help our kids rebuild a sense of worth, belonging, and confidence --all of which have connections to school performance, job opportunities, and personal relationships--to help them live up to their full potential. To achieve this goal, we operate a residential summer program in upstate New York as well as out-of-school time programs. Our college access programs consist of one-on-one guidance, group workshops (financial aid, choosing a college, personal statements, etc.), college tours, and parent support.

The Graduation Success Initiative (GSI) is a year-long, structured academic and personal support program designed to help motivated students graduate within one year. GSI is a program designed to support public assistance recipients' completion of associate degrees.

The Harlem Center for Education's Educational Opportunity Center provides low-income adults throughout New York City with free college access services. Our services include college admissions and financial aid application assistance, career counseling, academic advising, and adult education classes.

The Lang Youth Program is a six-year community outreach and education program that provides science enrichment, medical education, mentorship, and college preparation to youth, ages 12-18, from the Washington Heights and Inwood communities. The program offers a mini-medical school and public health curriculum, with opportunities including clinical rotations and internships that expose youth to a variety of healthcare careers. In addition, youth develop team-building, public speaking and presentation skills that prepare them for a successful future.

The NYU College Advising Corps (NYU CAC) aims to increase the number of low-income, first-generation, underrepresented high school students who enter and complete higher education.  NYU CAC places well-trained, recent NYU graduates as full-time college advisers in high-need partner high schools to help students through all steps of the college application process.  Advisers work closely with school staff and administration to foster a college-going culture within the schools they serve. From navigating college admissions, to securing SAT/ACT waivers and assisting students and their families with financial aid and scholarships, our advisers become experts, mentors, and student advocates.

The Options Center supports New Yorkers from all five boroughs to enroll in and persist at good-fit colleges. The heart of the program is one-to-one educational and financial aid counseling supplemented by group workshops, special events, college trips, campus visits, fee waivers, and last dollar grants and scholarships. The program is open to 11th and 12th grade NYC public and parochial school students as well as adults with a high school diploma or equivalency. Those who are applying to college for the first time or who are seeking to transfer or re-enroll are eligible.

The Pace federal TRIO Student Support Services (SSS) Program based on the New York City Campus provides intense and sustained support services to eligible low-income, first-generation and/or disabled undergraduate students with academic need to help them remain in college, advance steadily in their collegiate academic work and graduate in four-to-six years. SSS also provides career development support for both internship/job placement and the pursuit of professional or graduate school study.

The program is a sports-based youth development program that combines academic support with the sport of rowing. Our academic support includes after school tutoring, college application assistance, dorm support, and alumni outreach.
The program provices college access and alumni assistance for our low-income population.

The Single Stop Program at Guttman Community College (GCC) provides students and their families with social services that address barriers preventing them from attending and completing school. These services are provided in collaboration with GCC, Single Stop, and external partners.

column8: Baruch College Science and Technology Entry Program (STEP) Academy
column10: The STEP Academy at Baruch College is a science education and college preparation program that aims to build excitement around studying the sciences for the STEP-target population and to prepare these historically underrepresented or economically disadvantaged secondary school students for entry into postsecondary degree programs in scientific, technical, health related fields and the licensed professions. The STEP Academy is funded by the New York State Education Department.
The Urban Assembly supports our schools in providing the best possible education and counseling to our students so they are able to be successful in their postsecondary lives.

The Young Adult Program at Red Hook Initiative serves 150 young adult members ages 18-24 during the final stage of the RHI's Youth Empowerment Pipeline. The YAP houses two college access programs: (1) Pre-College Scholars supports young adults who aspire to enroll in college by assisting participants with securing their HSE and applying to college, (2) College Scholars supports Red Hook young adults who are working toward a two or four year college degree and provides college support in the form of bi-weekly check-ins, financial aid  assistance, scholarship application preparation, internship/interview support, and overall guidance and advocacy in navigating the college journey.

Turning Point Brooklyn's Education Center is a free, community-based adult literacy program that helps student meet their educational and life goals. We offer English (ESOL), Adult Basic Education (ABE), and High School Equivalency (HSE) classes, supportive counseling and case management, career readiness, and college access counseling & academic preparation.
We offer peer to peer mentoring as well as resume writing, internship opportunities and academic skills enhancement.

We offer support for college counselors, college access curriculum development, and near-peer mentoring trainings for high school and college students.  We also offer alumni programming and support.  CUNY Crew is a program serving 20 freshman at 4 community colleges.

We provide one on one and group mentoring for Black and Latino male high school students. The program includes personal and professional mentoring, and is facilitated by members of One Hundred Black Men.
We serve enrolled City College of New York students who are in temporary financial emergency. We assist them with short term grants that will enable them to remain in school.

column8: Double Discovery Center at Columbia University
column10: We serve first generation low income students in a comprehensive out-of-school time college access, preparation, and success program.
We serve low-income young women from all 5 boroughs. The young women come take classes in our central office located in mid-town.

We serve students who have participated previously in our elementary/middle school chess program. We provide comprehensive college prep services including: college prep & applications (college fairs, college apps & financial application guidance, SAT preparation, seminars, tutoring); summer programs (travel abroad, summer academy, summer college, internships); college tours; attending cultural events (museums, lectures, shows); and chess.

We work with students beginning in 9th grade, helping them explore and develop their college going identity.  We then follow our students throttle college process through one on one support and then through college graduation.

CARA works with schools and organizations to develop comprehensive, inquiry-driven college access programs. Working with teachers, counselors and administrators, we use organizational structures strategically to embed post-secondary exploration throughout students' high school years.

College Bridge supports first-generation college-bound students during their senior year and in the summer between high school graduation and college matriculation. CARA trains and supports current college students to work as “college coaches” in their alumni high schools, assisting graduating seniors as they navigate the many obstacles that arise during this critical time.

Graduate NYC was founded with the goal of 'doubling the number' of City University of New York (CUNY) graduates by 2020. Our projects include providing awareness and information on the college application process for students, professional development for high school teachers and college counselors as well as college faculty, in addition to serving as a funder of innovative projects intended to dramatically increase persistence and retention on college campuses throughout NYC.

Right to College works with schools and organizations to integrate Youth Leadership into their college access programming and

positions young people to engage their peers in the post-secondary planning process. Through comprehensive training and

support provided by CARA, Youth Leaders develop a range of skills and content knowledge that they use as a platform to make college access possible for a wider circle of students. Youth Leaders facilitate workshops; plan events; support other students in their search, application, and ?financial aid process; and work to promote an overall college-going culture within their institutions.

SSN serves youth development and education organizations who work with high school and middle school students by providing in person convenings, data analysis, continuous improvement support and online resource sharing around social emotional learning mindsets and behaviors.

Through a quick screening tool, students and their families learn their preliminary eligibility for public benefits, tax credits and community resources. Open to all New Yorkers, Single Stop offices in all 5 boroughs provide benefits counseling, legal assistance, financial counseling, tax preparation and social services.

Young Invincibles's New York Higher Education researches college access and success issues, produces policy reports with recommendations, and leads advocacy and organizing campaigns to impact the policy discourse in this area. YI also directly engages young adults to elevate their voices at the policy table.

Zone 126 is comprised of areas of concentrated poverty within zip codes 11101, 11102, and 11106.



Within our Zone are 3 major NYCHA developments:



11101: Queensbridge Houses

11102: Astoria Houses

11106: Ravenswood Houses

Zone 126 is committed to working with Collective Impact partners, community residents, and advocates in order to achieve the common mission of seeing all children from Astoria and Long Island City graduate from high school and attain a post-secondary education.

Blue Engine, seeking to close the gap between what it means to be college eligible and truly college ready, partners with public high schools serving low-income communities to increase academic rigor in core gateway subjects and prepare dramatically greater numbers of students for postsecondary success. 



Teams of Blue Engine Teaching Assistants work alongside lead teachers to provide data-driven, differentiated small group instruction in regularly scheduled math and English/Language Arts classes across the entire grade. BETAs provide additional personalized tutoring in extended learning time and also help students develop critical social cognitive competencies.

Supplemental Instruction and Small Group tutorials seek to bolster student learning and to strengthen classroom-based college level readiness of first year students enrolled in developmental and gateway courses.

column9: Graduate Support Program of Cornelia Connelly Center
column10: GSP serves graduates of Connelly Middle School during their high school and college careers. GSP provides academic support including, but not limited to free SAT prep classes and tutoring for high school students; financial support for high school tuition and college stipends; college preparation support such as college visits, application assistance, financial aid workshops; mentorship program; high school and college placement support; academic advising for students in high school and college.
The program offers college courses to qualifying junior and senior high school students.

The Early College Initiative develops and supports innovative public schools across New York City that provide students from a broad range of backgrounds the opportunity to earn both a high school diploma and an associate degree. The schools are designed to support students who have been historically underrepresented in higher education. 

Each early college school is developed as a partnership with a CUNY college, offering a coherent program of study to ensure students' success in high school, college, and beyond.

column8: CUNY Percy Ellis Sutton SEEK Programs
column9: CUNY Percy Ellis Sutton SEEK Programs
column10: If you are planning to attend a CUNY senior college as a first-time college student, we invite you to apply to the Percy Ellis Sutton SEEK program. This unique program provides eligible students with financial, academic, and counseling resources designed to help you earn your 4-year bachelors degree.

In our Access Program, we provide one on one counseling to low-income youth who are first generation to graduate from college in the US. We serve students after school and on weekends at our office in Downtown Brooklyn, but students come from all 5 boroughs.

We provide multiple college readiness and leadership services in an after-school setting, including tutoring and academic support; intensive coaching and counseling; enrichment, including arts, recreation and trips; college and career advisement; and exposure, including college fair trips and college tours in and out of state. The leadership program provides training and participation in youth-led projects. Groups are central to creating positive culture of excellence and connection.

College Now is CUNY's largest collaborative program with the New York City secondary public school system. The program offers dual enrollment and college-readiness programs in more than 400 NYC high schools and enrolls over 20,000 students annually. In all, there are seventeen campus-based College Now programs which are overseen by a central office.

SCS College Readiness Program prepares high school students and recent graduates ages 14-22 for the college admissions process. Through SAT classes, college admissions and financial aid workshops, college/university trips, college essay and application building sessions, reading/writing seminars, college roundtables and fairs, undergraduate mentorship and individual advisement, students become well versed on college admissions criteria, build their skills for standardized examinations, improve their writing, locate various scholarship opportunities and complete necessary applications for college admissions and financial aid while smoothly transitioning into their undergraduate years.
